<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-562-893  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 562 893.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>IBM System User  Sept 1990 p11(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Problems for automated operations. (includes a related article onautomated operations shakeout)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Rogers, Keith.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The push toward automated operations has not yet happened.andP;  Theidea of totally unattended computer centers is meeting resistanceand there are concerns about moving even to partial automation.andO;The political and practical problems within companies are the mainobstacles, not technical issues, such as threat of redundancies,need for retraining, and social and career concerns.andP;  The biggestinitial problem is fear of redundancy among operators and datacenter staff.andP;  The general view is that data center staff shouldbe able to move to the development or project management teams.andO;The thoroughness of the training program and the ability ofmanagement to handle the changes are what makes automation asuccess at the individual level.andP;  Many managers and companies areuneasy at the thought of leaving their data centers unattended.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Operations ServicesOperation of Computer SystemsOperations ManagersComputer OperatorsTrendsAutomation.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>